tributed to state-societal arrangements that have allowed one actor-labor in Britain, business in the United States-to dominate policymaking.Rival Capitalists will be an invaluable source for policymakers and business analysts as well as scholars and students of political economy, international relations, industrial organization, industrial sociology, and comparative politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aCompetition, International. 0aIndustrial policyzEuropean Economic Community countries. 0aIndustrial policyzJapan. 0aIndustrial policyzUnited States. 0aIndustrieszEuropean Economic Community countries. 0aIndustrieszJapan. 0aIndustrieszUnited States. 4aGeneral Economics. 4aPolitical Science & Political History.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172553140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501725531423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501725531/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles